04408nam a22006735i 9780801462559DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577205  a97808014625597 a10.7591/97808014625592doi  a(DE-B1597)478276  a(OCoLC)732957078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBIO0070002bisacsh04a891.73 32221 aNickell, William S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death of Tolstoy :bRussia on the Eve, Astapovo Station, 1910 /cWilliam S. Nickell. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b25 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Family Crisis as a Public Event -- t2. Narrative Transfigurations of Tolstoy’s Final Journey -- t3. The Media at Astapovo and the Creation of a Modern Pastoral -- t4. Tolstoyan Violence upon the Funeral Rites of the State -- t5. On or About November 1910 -- tConclusion: The Posthumous Notes of Fyodor Kuzmich -- tA Word on My Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the middle of the night of October 28, 1910, Leo Tolstoy, the most famous man in Russia, vanished. A secular saint revered for his literary genius, pacificism, and dedication to the earth and the poor, Tolstoy had left his home in secret to embark on a final journey. His disappearance immediately became a national sensation. Two days later he was located at a monastery, but was soon gone again. When he turned up next at Astapovo, a small, remote railway station, all of Russia was following the story. As he lay dying of pneumonia, he became the hero of a national narrative of immense significance.In The Death of Tolstoy, William Nickell describes a Russia engaged in a war of words over how this story should be told. The Orthodox Church, which had excommunicated Tolstoy in 1901, first argued that he had returned to the fold and then came out against his beliefs more vehemently than ever. Police spies sent by the state tracked his every move, fearing that his death would embolden his millions of supporters among the young, the peasantry, and the intelligentsia. Representatives of the press converged on the stationhouse at Astapovo where Tolstoy lay ill, turning his death into a feverish media event that strikingly anticipated today's no-limits coverage of celebrity lives—and deaths.Drawing on newspaper accounts, personal correspondence, police reports, secret circulars, telegrams, letters, and memoirs, Nickell shows the public spectacle of Tolstoy's last days to be a vivid reflection of a fragile, anxious empire on the eve of war and revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146255940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801462559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801462559/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK